{
  "doc_id": "15903",
  "text": "It appears that without a great deal of locomotor experience with a wheelchair, participants were unable to adapt to locomotor constraints imposed during wheelchair use and/or to effectively use optic flow to guide wheelchair locomotion. Attributing the specific patterns of fixation under the wheelchair condition to unfamiliarity with wheelchair use is indirectly supported by the findings demonstrating that a great deal of practice is necessary to effectively use optical variables in motor control [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This is referred to as perceptual attunement. The existence of perceptual attunement has been demonstrated with perceptual-motor tasks, such as judging optic angles or the expansion rate of an approaching ball [CITATION_4] . It seems likely that similar learning process is necessary to effectively use optical variables during adaptive locomotion.",
